# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bloom-effect
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bloom-effect/bloom-shader-effect] There are two recognized potential causes of bloom.
[src:bloom-effect/bloom-shader-effect] One physical basis of bloom is that, in the real world, lenses can never focus perfectly.
[src:bloom-effect/bloom-shader-effect] Even a perfect lens will convolve the incoming image with an Airy disk (the diffraction pattern produced by passing a point light source through a circular aperture).
[src:bloom-effect/bloom-shader-effect] Under normal circumstances, these imperfections are not noticeable, but an intensely bright light source will cause the imperfections to become visible.
[src:bloom-effect/bloom-shader-effect] As a result, the image of the bright light appears to bleed beyond its natural borders.
[src:bloom-effect/bloom-shader-effect] The Airy disc function falls off very quickly but has very wide tails (actually, infinitely wide tails).
[src:bloom-effect/bloom-shader-effect] In HDRR images, the effect can be reproduced by convolving the image with a windowed kernel of an Airy disc (for very good lenses), or by applying Gaussian blur (to simulate the effect of a less perfect lens), before converting the image to fixed-range pixels.
[src:bloom-effect/bloom-shader-effect] The effect cannot be fully reproduced in non-HDRR imaging systems, because the amount of bleed depends on how bright the bright part of the image is.
[src:bloom-effect/bloom-shader-effect] As an example, when a picture is taken indoors, the brightness of outdoor objects seen through a window may be 70 or 80 times brighter than objects inside the room.
[src:bloom-effect/bloom-shader-effect] If exposure levels are set for objects inside the room, the bright image of the windows will bleed past the window frames when convolved with the Airy disc of the camera being used to produce the image.
[src:bloom-effect/bloom-shader-effect] Bloom in digital cameras is caused by an overflow of charge in the photodiodes, which are the light-sensitive elements in the camera's image sensor.
[src:bloom-effect/bloom-shader-effect] When a photodiode is exposed to a very bright light source, the accumulated charge can spill over into adjacent pixels, creating a halo effect.
[src:bloom-effect/bloom-shader-effect] The bloom effect is more pronounced in cameras with smaller pixels, as there is less room for the charge to dissipate.
[src:bloom-effect/bloom-shader-effect] It can also be exacerbated by high ISO settings, which increase the camera's sensitivity to light and can result in more charge accumulation.
[src:bloom-effect/bloom-shader-effect] While the bloom effect can be distracting in some images, it can also be used creatively to add a dreamy or otherworldly quality to photos.
[src:bloom-effect/bloom-shader-effect] Current generation gaming systems are able to render 3D graphics using floating-point frame buffers, in order to produce HDR images.
[src:bloom-effect/bloom-shader-effect] To produce the bloom effect, the linear HDRR image in the frame buffer is convolved with a convolution kernel in a post-processing step, before converting to RGB space.
[src:bloom-effect/bloom-shader-effect] The convolution step usually requires the use of a large gaussian kernel that is not practical for realtime graphics, causing programmers to use approximation methods.
[src:bloom-effect/bloom-shader-effect] Some of the earliest games to use the bloom effect include the pre-rendered CGI game *Riven* (1997), the voxel game *Outcast* (1999), and the real-time 3D polygon games *The Bouncer* (2000) and *Ico* (2001).
[src:bloom-effect/bloom-shader-effect] Bloom was later popularized within the game development community in 2004, when an article on the technique was published by the authors of *Tron 2.0*.
[src:bloom-effect/bloom-shader-effect] Bloom lighting has been used in many games, modifications and game engines such as *Quake Live*, *Cube 2: Sauerbraten* and the Spring game engine.
[src:bloom-effect/bloom-shader-effect] The effect was popular in 7th-generation games, which were released from 2005 through to the early 2010s.
[src:bloom-effect/bloom-shader-effect] Several games from the period have received criticism for overuse of the technique.
[src:bloom-effect/bloom-shader-effect] The heavy bloom lighting in *RollerCoaster Tycoon 3* (2005) was described as "disgusting" at the time by GameSpot.
[src:bloom-effect/bloom-shader-effect] Gaming Bolt described the trend as a gimmick that had died with the generation, and criticised the heavy use of the technique in major releases of the time such as *The Elder Scrolls IV: Oblivion* (2006), the Xbox 360 port of *Burnout Revenge* (2006), and *Zelda: Twilight Princess* (2006).
[src:bloom-effect/bloom-shader-effect] *Syndicate* (2012) has also been described as featuring "eye-melting" bloom.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] In mathematics (in particular, functional analysis), **convolution** is a mathematical operation on two functions f and g that produces a third function $f*g$ , as the integral of the product of the two functions after one is reflected about the y-axis and shifted.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] The term *convolution* refers to both the resulting function and to the process of computing it.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] The integral is evaluated for all values of shift, producing the convolution function.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] The choice of which function is reflected and shifted before the integral does not change the integral result (see commutativity).
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Graphically, it expresses how the 'shape' of one function is modified by the other.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] For complex-valued functions, the cross-correlation operator is the adjoint of the convolution operator.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Convolution has applications that include probability, statistics, acoustics, spectroscopy, signal processing and image processing, computer vision and human vision, geophysics, engineering, physics, and differential equations.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] The convolution can be defined for functions on Euclidean space and other groups (as algebraic structures).
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] For example, periodic functions, such as the discrete-time Fourier transform, can be defined on a circle and convolved by periodic convolution.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] (See row 18 at DTFT § Properties.) A *discrete convolution* can be defined for functions on the set of integers.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Generalizations of convolution have applications in the field of numerical analysis and numerical linear algebra, and in the design and implementation of finite impulse response filters in signal processing.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Computing the inverse of the convolution operation is known as deconvolution.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] The convolution of f and g is written $f*g$ , denoting the operator with the symbol * .
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] It is defined as the integral of the product of the two functions after one is reflected about the y-axis and shifted.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] While the symbol t is used above, it need not represent the time domain.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] At each t , the convolution formula can be described as the area under the function $f(\tau )$ weighted by the function $g(-\tau )$ shifted by the amount t .
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] For the multi-dimensional formulation of convolution, see *domain of definition* (below).
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] which has to be interpreted carefully to avoid confusion.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] respectively, the convolution operation $(f*g)(t)$ can be defined as the inverse Laplace transform of the product of $F(s)$ and $G(s)$ .
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Note that $F(s)\cdot G(s)$ is the bilateral Laplace transform of $(f*g)(t)$ .
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] A similar derivation can be done using the unilateral Laplace transform (one-sided Laplace transform).
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] The convolution operation also describes the output (in terms of the input) of an important class of operations known as *linear time-invariant* (LTI).
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] See LTI system theory for a derivation of convolution as the result of LTI constraints.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] In terms of the Fourier transforms of the input and output of an LTI operation, no new frequency components are created.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] The existing ones are only modified (amplitude and/or phase).
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] In other words, the output transform is the pointwise product of the input transform with a third transform (known as a transfer function).
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] See Convolution theorem for a derivation of that property of convolution.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Conversely, convolution can be derived as the inverse Fourier transform of the pointwise product of two Fourier transforms.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] One of the earliest uses of the convolution integral appeared in D'Alembert's derivation of Taylor's theorem in *Recherches sur différents points importants du système du monde,* published in 1754.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] is used by Sylvestre François Lacroix on page 505 of his book entitled *Treatise on differences and series*, which is the last of 3 volumes of the encyclopedic series: *Traité du calcul différentiel et du calcul intégral*, Chez Courcier, Paris, 1797–1800.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Soon thereafter, convolution operations appear in the works of Pierre Simon Laplace, Jean-Baptiste Joseph Fourier, Siméon Denis Poisson, and others.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] The term itself did not come into wide use until the 1950s or 1960s.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Prior to that it was sometimes known as *Faltung* (which means *folding* in German), *composition product*, *superposition integral*, and *Carson's integral*.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Yet it appears as early as 1903, though the definition is rather unfamiliar in older uses.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] is a particular case of composition products considered by the Italian mathematician Vito Volterra in 1913.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] The summation is called a periodic summation of the function f .
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] When $g_{T}$ is a periodic summation of another function, g , then $f*g_{T}$ is known as a *circular* or *cyclic* convolution of f and g .
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] And if the periodic summation above is replaced by $f_{T}$ , the operation is called a *periodic* convolution of $f_{T}$ and $g_{T}$ .
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] The convolution of two finite sequences is defined by extending the sequences to finitely supported functions on the set of integers.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] When the sequences are the coefficients of two polynomials, then the coefficients of the ordinary product of the two polynomials are the convolution of the original two sequences.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] This is known as the Cauchy product of the coefficients of the sequences.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] The notation $f*_{N}g$ for *cyclic convolution* denotes convolution over the cyclic group of integers modulo *N*.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Circular convolution arises most often in the context of fast convolution with a fast Fourier transform (FFT) algorithm.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] In many situations, discrete convolutions can be converted to circular convolutions so that fast transforms with a convolution property can be used to implement the computation.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] For example, convolution of digit sequences is the kernel operation in multiplication of multi-digit numbers, which can therefore be efficiently implemented with transform techniques (Knuth 1997, §4.3.3.C; von zur Gathen & Gerhard 2003, §8.2).
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] The most common fast convolution algorithms use fast Fourier transform (FFT) algorithms via the circular convolution theorem.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Specifically, the circular convolution of two finite-length sequences is found by taking an FFT of each sequence, multiplying pointwise, and then performing an inverse FFT.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Convolutions of the type defined above are then efficiently implemented using that technique in conjunction with zero-extension and/or discarding portions of the output.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Other fast convolution algorithms, such as the Schönhage–Strassen algorithm or the Mersenne transform, use fast Fourier transforms in other rings.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] The Winograd method is used as an alternative to the FFT.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] It significantly speeds up 1D, 2D, and 3D convolution.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] If one sequence is much longer than the other, zero-extension of the shorter sequence and fast circular convolution is not the most computationally efficient method available.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Instead, decomposing the longer sequence into blocks and convolving each block allows for faster algorithms such as the overlap–save method and overlap–add method.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] A hybrid convolution method that combines block and FIR algorithms allows for a zero input-output latency that is useful for real-time convolution computations.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] and is well-defined only if f and g decay sufficiently rapidly at infinity in order for the integral to exist.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Conditions for the existence of the convolution may be tricky, since a blow-up in g at infinity can be easily offset by sufficiently rapid decay in f.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] If f and g are compactly supported continuous functions, then their convolution exists, and is also compactly supported and continuous (Hörmander 1983, Chapter 1).
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] More generally, if either function (say f) is compactly supported and the other is locally integrable, then the convolution *f*∗*g* is well-defined and continuous.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Convolution of f and g is also well defined when both functions are locally square integrable on **R** and supported on an interval of the form [*a*, +∞) (or both supported on [−∞, *a*]).
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] The convolution of f and g exists if f and g are both Lebesgue integrable functions in *L*1(**R***d*), and in this case *f*∗*g* is also integrable (Stein & Weiss 1971, Theorem 1.3).
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] This is a consequence of Tonelli's theorem.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] This is also true for functions in *L*1, under the discrete convolution, or more generally for the convolution on any group.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] In the particular case *p* = 1, this shows that *L*1 is a Banach algebra under the convolution (and equality of the two sides holds if f and g are non-negative almost everywhere).
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] More generally, Young's inequality implies that the convolution is a continuous bilinear map between suitable *L**p* spaces.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] so that the convolution is a continuous bilinear mapping from *L**p*×*L**q* to *L**r*.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] The Young inequality for convolution is also true in other contexts (circle group, convolution on **Z**).
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] The optimal value of *B**p*,*q* was discovered in 1975 and independently in 1976, see Brascamp–Lieb inequality.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] In addition to compactly supported functions and integrable functions, functions that have sufficiently rapid decay at infinity can also be convolved.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] An important feature of the convolution is that if *f* and *g* both decay rapidly, then *f*∗*g* also decays rapidly.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] In particular, if *f* and *g* are rapidly decreasing functions, then so is the convolution *f*∗*g*.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Combined with the fact that convolution commutes with differentiation (see #Properties), it follows that the class of Schwartz functions is closed under convolution (Stein & Weiss 1971, Theorem 3.3).
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] remains valid in the case where *f* is a distribution, and *g* a compactly supported distribution (Hörmander 1983, §4.2).
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] where $A\subset \mathbf {R} ^{d}$ is a measurable set and $1_{A}$ is the indicator function of A .
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] This agrees with the convolution defined above when μ and ν are regarded as distributions, as well as the convolution of L1 functions when μ and ν are absolutely continuous with respect to the Lebesgue measure.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] where the norm is the total variation of a measure.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Because the space of measures of bounded variation is a Banach space, convolution of measures can be treated with standard methods of functional analysis that may not apply for the convolution of distributions.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] The convolution defines a product on the linear space of integrable functions.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] This product satisfies the following algebraic properties, which formally mean that the space of integrable functions with the product given by convolution is a commutative associative algebra without identity (Strichartz 1994, §3.3).
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Other linear spaces of functions, such as the space of continuous functions of compact support, are closed under the convolution, and so also form commutative associative algebras.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] (i.e., double integrals can be evaluated as iterated integrals in either order).
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Proof: This follows from linearity of the integral.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] No algebra of functions possesses an identity for the convolution.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] The linear space of compactly supported distributions does, however, admit an identity under the convolution.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] The same result holds if *f* and *g* are only assumed to be nonnegative measurable functions, by Tonelli's theorem.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] where ${\frac {d}{dx}}$ is the derivative.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] A particular consequence of this is that the convolution can be viewed as a "smoothing" operation: the convolution of *f* and *g* is differentiable as many times as *f* and *g* are in total.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] These identities hold for example under the condition that *f* and *g* are absolutely integrable and at least one of them has an absolutely integrable (L1) weak derivative, as a consequence of Young's convolution inequality.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] These identities also hold much more broadly in the sense of tempered distributions if one of *f* or *g* is a rapidly decreasing tempered distribution, a compactly supported tempered distribution or a Schwartz function and the other is a tempered distribution.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] On the other hand, two positive integrable and infinitely differentiable functions may have a nowhere continuous convolution.
