[src:bloom-effect/convolution] from the properties of the face-splitting product.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] If *f* is a Schwartz function, then *τxf* is the convolution with a translated Dirac delta function *τ**x**f* = *f* ∗ *τ**x* *δ*.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] So translation invariance of the convolution of Schwartz functions is a consequence of the associativity of convolution.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Furthermore, under certain conditions, convolution is the most general translation invariant operation.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Thus some translation invariant operations can be represented as convolution.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Convolutions play an important role in the study of time-invariant systems, and especially LTI system theory.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] The representing function *g**S* is the impulse response of the transformation *S*.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] A more precise version of the theorem quoted above requires specifying the class of functions on which the convolution is defined, and also requires assuming in addition that *S* must be a continuous linear operator with respect to the appropriate topology.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] It is known, for instance, that every continuous translation invariant continuous linear operator on *L*1 is the convolution with a finite Borel measure.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] More generally, every continuous translation invariant continuous linear operator on *L**p* for 1 ≤ *p* < ∞ is the convolution with a tempered distribution whose Fourier transform is bounded.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] To wit, they are all given by bounded Fourier multipliers.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] In typical cases of interest *G* is a locally compact Hausdorff topological group and λ is a (left-) Haar measure.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] In that case, unless *G* is unimodular, the convolution defined in this way is not the same as ${\textstyle \int f\left(xy^{-1}\right)g(y)\,d\lambda (y)}$ .
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Furthermore, the convention is also required for consistency with the definition of the convolution of measures given below.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] However, with a right instead of a left Haar measure, the latter integral is preferred over the former.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] On locally compact abelian groups, a version of the convolution theorem holds: the Fourier transform of a convolution is the pointwise product of the Fourier transforms.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] The circle group **T** with the Lebesgue measure is an immediate example.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] By the commutativity property cited above, *T* is normal: *T** *T* = *TT** .
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Also, *T* commutes with the translation operators.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Consider the family *S* of operators consisting of all such convolutions and the translation operators.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Then *S* is a commuting family of normal operators.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] According to spectral theory, there exists an orthonormal basis {*hk*} that simultaneously diagonalizes *S*.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] This characterizes convolutions on the circle.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] which are precisely the characters of **T**.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Each convolution is a compact multiplication operator in this basis.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] This can be viewed as a version of the convolution theorem discussed above.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] A discrete example is a finite cyclic group of order *n*.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Convolution operators are here represented by circulant matrices, and can be diagonalized by the discrete Fourier transform.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Let *G* be a (multiplicatively written) topological group.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] In fact, if *either* measure is absolutely continuous with respect to the Haar measure, then so is their convolution.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] If μ and ν are probability measures on the topological group (**R**,+), then the convolution *μ*∗*ν* is the probability distribution of the sum *X* + *Y* of two independent random variables *X* and *Y* whose respective distributions are μ and ν.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Let (*X*, Δ, ∇, *ε*, *η*) be a bialgebra with comultiplication Δ, multiplication ∇, unit η, and counit *ε*.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] The convolution is a product defined on the endomorphism algebra End(*X*) as follows.
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] The convolution appears notably in the definition of Hopf algebras (Kassel 1995, §III.3).
[src:bloom-effect/convolution] Convolution and related operations are found in many applications in science, engineering and mathematics.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] In image processing, a **Gaussian blur** (also known as **Gaussian smoothing**) is the result of blurring an image by a Gaussian function (named after mathematician and scientist Carl Friedrich Gauss).
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] It is a widely used effect in graphics software, typically to reduce image noise and reduce definition.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] The visual effect of this blurring technique is a smooth blur resembling that of viewing the image through a translucent screen, distinctly different from the bokeh effect produced by an out-of-focus lens or the shadow of an object under usual illumination.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] Gaussian smoothing is also used as a pre-processing stage in computer vision algorithms in order to enhance image structures at different scales—see scale space representation and scale space implementation.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] Mathematically, applying a Gaussian blur to an image is the same as convolving the image with a Gaussian function.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] This is also known as a two-dimensional Weierstrass transform.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] By contrast, convolving by a circle (i.e., a circular box blur) would more accurately reproduce the bokeh effect.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] Since the Fourier transform of a Gaussian is another Gaussian, applying a Gaussian blur has the effect of reducing the image's high-frequency components; a Gaussian blur is thus a low-pass filter.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] The Gaussian blur is a type of image-blurring filter that uses a Gaussian function (which also expresses the normal distribution in statistics) for calculating the transformation to apply to each pixel in the image.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] The origin on these axes are at the center (0, 0).
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] When applied in two dimensions, this formula produces a surface whose contours are concentric circles with a Gaussian distribution from the center point.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] Values from this distribution are used to build a convolution matrix which is applied to the original image.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] This convolution process is illustrated visually in the figure on the right.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] Each pixel's new value is set to a weighted average of that pixel's neighborhood.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] The original pixel's value receives the heaviest weight (having the highest Gaussian value) and neighboring pixels receive smaller weights as their distance to the original pixel increases.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] This results in a blur that preserves boundaries and edges better than other, more uniform blurring filters; see also scale space implementation.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] In theory, the Gaussian function at every point on the image will be non-zero, meaning that the entire image would need to be included in the calculations for each pixel.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] In practice, when computing a discrete approximation of the Gaussian function, pixels at a distance of more than 3*σ* have a small enough influence to be considered effectively zero.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] Thus contributions from pixels outside that range can be ignored.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] Typically, an image processing program need only calculate a matrix with dimensions $\lceil 6\sigma \rceil$ × $\lceil 6\sigma \rceil$ (where $\lceil \cdot \rceil$ is the ceiling function) to ensure a result sufficiently close to that obtained by the entire Gaussian distribution.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] In addition to being circularly symmetric, the Gaussian blur can be applied to a two-dimensional image as two independent one-dimensional calculations, and so is termed a separable filter.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] That is, the effect of applying the two-dimensional matrix can also be achieved by applying a series of single-dimensional Gaussian matrices in the horizontal direction, then repeating the process in the vertical direction.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] Applying successive Gaussian blurs to an image has the same effect as applying a single, larger Gaussian blur, whose radius is the square root of the sum of the squares of the blur radii that were actually applied.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] For example, applying successive Gaussian blurs with radii of 6 and 8 gives the same results as applying a single Gaussian blur of radius 10, since ${\sqrt {6^{2}+8^{2}}}=10$ .
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] Because of this relationship, processing time cannot be saved by simulating a Gaussian blur with successive, smaller blurs — the time required will be at least as great as performing the single large blur.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] Gaussian blurring is commonly used when reducing the size of an image.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] When downsampling an image, it is common to apply a low-pass filter to the image prior to resampling.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] This is to ensure that spurious high-frequency information does not appear in the downsampled image (aliasing).
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] Gaussian blurs have nice properties, such as having no sharp edges, and thus do not introduce ringing into the filtered image.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] Gaussian blur is a low-pass filter, attenuating high frequency signals.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] Its amplitude Bode plot (the log scale in the frequency domain) is a parabola.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] This sample matrix is produced by sampling the Gaussian filter kernel (with σ = 0.84089642) at the midpoints of each pixel and then normalizing.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] The center element (at [0, 0]) has the largest value, decreasing symmetrically as distance from the center increases.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] Since the filter kernel's origin is at the center, the matrix starts at ${\textstyle G(-R,-R)}$ and ends at ${\textstyle G(R,R)}$ where R equals the kernel radius.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] The element 0.22508352 (the central one) is 1177 times larger than 0.00019117 which is just outside 3σ.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] A Gaussian blur effect is typically generated by convolving an image with an FIR kernel of Gaussian values.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] In practice, it is best to take advantage of the Gaussian blur’s separable property by dividing the process into two passes.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] In the first pass, a one-dimensional kernel is used to blur the image in only the horizontal or vertical direction.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] In the second pass, the same one-dimensional kernel is used to blur in the remaining direction.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] Discretization is typically achieved by sampling the Gaussian filter kernel at discrete points, normally at positions corresponding to the midpoints of each pixel.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] This reduces the computational cost but, for very small filter kernels, point sampling the Gaussian function with very few samples leads to a large error.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] In these cases, accuracy is maintained (at a slight computational cost) by integration of the Gaussian function over each pixel's area.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] When converting the Gaussian’s continuous values into the discrete values needed for a kernel, the sum of the values will be different from 1.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] This will cause a darkening or brightening of the image.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] To remedy this, the values can be normalized by dividing each term in the kernel by the sum of all terms in the kernel.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] For a more detailed description about the discrete analogue of the Gaussian kernel, see the article on scale-space implementation and.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] The efficiency of FIR breaks down for high sigmas.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] These include the very fast multiple box blurs, the fast and accurate IIR Deriche edge detector, a "stack blur" based on the box blur, and more.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] For processing pre-recorded temporal signals or video, the Gaussian kernel can also be used for smoothing over the temporal domain, since the data are pre-recorded and available in all directions.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] When processing temporal signals or video in real-time situations, the Gaussian kernel cannot, however, be used for temporal smoothing, since it would access data from the future, which obviously cannot be available.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] The time-causal limit kernel corresponds to convolution with an infinite number of truncated exponential kernels coupled in cascade, with specifically chosen time constants.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] For discrete data, this kernel can often be numerically well approximated by a small set of first-order recursive filters coupled in cascade, see for further details.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] Gaussian smoothing is commonly used with edge detection.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] Most edge-detection algorithms are sensitive to noise; the 2-D Laplacian filter, built from a discretization of the Laplace operator, is highly sensitive to noisy environments.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] Using a Gaussian Blur filter before edge detection aims to reduce the level of noise in the image, which improves the result of the following edge-detection algorithm.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] This approach is commonly referred to as Laplacian of Gaussian, or LoG filtering.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] Lower-end digital cameras, including many mobile phone cameras, commonly use gaussian blurring to obscure image noise caused by higher ISO light sensitivities.
[src:bloom-effect/gaussian-blur] Gaussian blur is automatically applied as part of the image post-processing of the photo by the camera software, leading to an irreversible loss of detail.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] Glare can be generally divided into two types, discomfort glare and disability glare.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] Discomfort glare is a psychological sensation caused by high brightness (or brightness contrast) within the field of view, which does not necessarily impair vision.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] In buildings, discomfort glare can originate from small artificial lights (e.g. ceiling fixtures) that have brightnesses that are significantly greater than their surrounding.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] When the luminous source occupies a much greater portion of the visual field (e.g. daylit windows), discomfort caused by glare can be linked to a saturating effect.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] Since observers will not always look directly at a bright illuminated source, discomfort glare usually arises when an observer is focusing on a visual task (e.g. a computer-screen) and the bright source is within their peripheral visual field.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] Disability glare impairs the vision of objects without necessarily causing discomfort.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] This could arise for instance when driving westward at sunset.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] Disability glare is often caused by the inter-reflection of light within the eyeball, reducing the contrast between task and glare source to the point where the task cannot be distinguished.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] When glare is so intense that vision is completely impaired, it is sometimes called **dazzle**.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] Sunglasses are often worn to reduce glare; polarized sunglasses are designed to reduce glare caused by light reflected from non-metallic surfaces such as water, glossy printed matter or painted surfaces.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] An anti-reflective treatment on eyeglasses reduces the glare at night and glare from inside lights and computer screens that is caused by light bouncing off the lens.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] Some types of eyeglasses can reduce glare that occurs because of the imperfections on the surface of the eye.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] Light field measurements can be taken to reduce glare with digital post-processing.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] Discomfort glare has often been studied using psychophysics experiments, where the common methods have been the luminance adjustment and category rating procedures.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] Studies conducted by Petherbridge and Hopkinson and Luckiesh and Guth. were amongst the first to compared subjective assessments given by observers against physical measurements produced by a glare source.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] A comprehensive review of the methods used to measure glare showed that there are biases associated with its measurement.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] Luminance adjustments are sensitive to anchoring effects caused when the initial starting luminance viewed influences the final assessment of visual discomfort.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] Glare is also subject to stimulus range bias effects.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] This occurs when the luminance range influences the final evaluation of glare given by the observer.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] A larger range, often results in higher glare evaluations given.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] Glare from artificial lights is typically measured with luminance meters.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] From daylit windows, cameras are used to convert the pixels into luminance.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] Both of which are able to determine the luminance of objects within small solid angles.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] The glare of a scene i.e. visual field of view, is then calculated from the luminance data of that scene.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] The CIE recommends the *Unified glare rating* (UGR) as a quantitative measure of glare.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] Other glare calculation methods include *CIBSE Glare Index*, *IES Glare Index* and the *Daylight Glare Index* (DGI).
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] The Unified Glare Rating (UGR) is a measure of the glare in a given environment, accounting only interior artificial lights, proposed by Sorensen in 1987 and adopted by the International Commission on Illumination (CIE).
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] Where $\log$ is the common logarithm (base 10), $L_{n}$ is the luminance of each light source numbered n , $\omega _{n}$ is the solid angle of the light source seen from the observer and $p_{n}$ is the Guth Position Index, which depends on the distance from the line of sight of the viewer.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] The Daylight Glare Probability (DGP) is a measure glare from real daylight condition in side-lit room within the field of view from curtain position, not considering for artificial light.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] It considers illuminance and luminance from glare sources to estimate the level of dissatisfaction.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] DGP was proposed by Wienold and Christoffersen in 2006 and adopted as first ever day-lighting standard by the European Standard's EN 17037 (2018) Daylight in Buildings.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] The EN 17037 glare assessment helps designer to determine shading need, transmission of glazing if the DGP is higher than 0.4.
[src:bloom-effect/glare-vision] However, data from tropical climate countries suggests the DGP threshold is expected to be 0.24, significant lower than Wienold and Christoffersen's Copenhagen and Freiburg data.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Graphics processor company Nvidia summarizes the motivation for HDRR in three points: bright things can be really bright, dark things can be really dark, and details can be seen in both.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] The use of high-dynamic-range imaging (HDRI) in computer graphics was introduced by Greg Ward in 1985 with his open-source Radiance rendering and *lighting simulation* software which created the first file format to retain a high-dynamic-range image.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] HDRI languished for more than a decade, held back by limited computing power, storage, and capture methods.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Not until recently has the technology to put HDRI into practical use been developed.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] In 1990, Eihachiro Nakame and associates presented a lighting model for driving simulators that highlighted the need for high-dynamic-range processing in realistic simulations.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] In 1995, Greg Spencer presented *Physically-based glow visual effects for digital images* at SIGGRAPH, providing a quantitative model for flare and blooming in the human eye.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] In 1997, Paul Debevec presented *Recovering high dynamic range radiance maps from photographs* at SIGGRAPH, and the following year presented *Rendering synthetic objects into real scenes*.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] These two papers laid the framework for creating HDR *light probes* of a location, and then using this probe to light a rendered scene.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] HDRI and HDRL (high-dynamic-range image-based lighting) have, ever since, been used in many situations in 3D scenes in which inserting a 3D object into a real environment requires the light probe data to provide realistic lighting solutions.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] In gaming applications, *Riven: The Sequel to Myst* in 1997 used an HDRI postprocessing shader directly based on Spencer's paper.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] After E3 2003, Valve released a demo movie of their Source engine rendering a cityscape in a high dynamic range.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] The term was not commonly used again until E3 2004, where it gained much more attention when Epic Games showcased Unreal Engine 3 and Valve announced *Half-Life 2: Lost Coast* in 2005, coupled with open-source engines such as OGRE 3D and open-source games like *Nexuiz*.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] By the 2010s, HDR displays first became available.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] With higher contrast ratios, HDRR can reduce or eliminate tone mapping, resulting in an even more realistic image.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] One of the primary advantages of HDR rendering is that details in a scene with a large contrast ratio are preserved.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Without HDRR, areas that are too dark are clipped to black and areas that are too bright are clipped to white.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] These are represented by the hardware as a floating point value of 0.0 and 1.0 for pure black and pure white, respectively.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Another aspect of HDR rendering is the addition of perceptual cues which increase apparent brightness.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] HDR rendering also affects how light is preserved in optical phenomena such as reflections and refractions, as well as transparent materials such as glass.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] In LDR rendering, very bright light sources in a scene (such as the sun) are capped at 1.0.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] When this light is reflected the result must then be less than or equal to 1.0.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] However, in HDR rendering, very bright light sources can exceed the 1.0 brightness to simulate their actual values.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] This allows reflections off surfaces to maintain realistic brightness for bright light sources.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] The human eye can perceive scenes with a very high dynamic contrast ratio, around 1,000,000:1.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Adaptation is achieved in part through adjustments of the iris and slow chemical changes, which take some time (e.g. the delay in being able to see when switching from bright lighting to pitch darkness).
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] At any given time, the eye's static range is smaller, around 10,000:1.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] However, this is still higher than the static range of most display technology.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Although many manufacturers claim very high numbers, plasma displays, liquid-crystal displays, and CRT displays can deliver only a fraction of the contrast ratio found in the real world, and these are usually measured under ideal conditions.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] The simultaneous contrast of real content under normal viewing conditions is significantly lower.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Some increase in dynamic range in LCD monitors can be achieved by automatically reducing the backlight for dark scenes.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] For example, LG calls this technology "Digital Fine Contrast"; Samsung describes it as "dynamic contrast ratio".
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Another technique is to have an array of brighter and darker LED backlights, for example with systems developed by BrightSide Technologies.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] OLED displays have better dynamic range capabilities than LCDs, similar to plasma but with lower power consumption.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] 709 defines the color space for HDTV, and Rec.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] 2020 defines a larger but still incomplete color space for ultra-high-definition television.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Since the 2010s, OLED and other HDR display technologies have reduced or eliminated the need for tone mapping HDRR to standard dynamic range.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Light blooming is the result of scattering in the human lens, which human brain interprets as a bright spot in a scene.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] For example, a bright light in the background will appear to bleed over onto objects in the foreground.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] This can be used to create an illusion to make the bright spot appear to be brighter than it really is.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Flare is the diffraction of light in the human lens, resulting in "rays" of light emanating from small light sources, and can also result in some chromatic effects.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] It is most visible on point light sources because of their small visual angle.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Typical display devices cannot display light as bright as the Sun, and ambient room lighting prevents them from displaying true black.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Thus, HDR rendering systems have to map the full dynamic range of what the eye would see in the rendered situation onto the capabilities of the device.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] This tone mapping is done relative to what the virtual scene camera sees, combined with several full screen effects, e.g. to simulate dust in the air which is lit by direct sunlight in a dark cavern, or the scattering in the eye.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Tone mapping and blooming shaders can be used together to help simulate these effects.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Tone mapping, in the context of graphics rendering, is a technique used to map colors from high dynamic range (in which lighting calculations are performed) to a lower dynamic range that matches the capabilities of the desired display device.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Typically, the mapping is non-linear – it preserves enough range for dark colors and gradually limits the dynamic range for bright colors.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] This technique often produces visually appealing images with good overall detail and contrast.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Various tone mapping operators exist, ranging from simple real-time methods used in computer games to more sophisticated techniques that attempt to imitate the perceptual response of the human visual system.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] HDR displays with higher dynamic range capabilities can reduce or eliminate the tone mapping required after HDRR, resulting in an even more realistic image.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Currently HDRR has been prevalent in games, primarily for PCs but was previously prevalent in Microsoft's Xbox 360and Sony's PlayStation 3.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] It has also been simulated on the PlayStation 2, GameCube, Xbox and Amiga systems.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Sproing Interactive Media had announced that their Athena game engine for the Wii will support HDRR, which added the Wii to the list of systems that support it.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] In desktop publishing and gaming, color values are often processed several times over.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] As this includes multiplication and division (which can accumulate rounding errors), it is useful to have the extended accuracy and range of 16-bit integer or 16-bit floating point formats.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] This is useful irrespective of the aforementioned limitations in some hardware.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Complex shader effects began their days with the release of Shader Model 1.0 with DirectX 8.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Shader Model 1.0 illuminated 3D worlds with what is called standard lighting.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Lighting calculations were integer based, which didn't offer as much accuracy because the real world is not confined to whole numbers.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] On December 24, 2002, Microsoft released a new version of DirectX.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] DirectX 9.0 introduced Shader Model 2.0, which offered one of the necessary components to enable rendering of high-dynamic-range images: lighting precision was not limited to just 8-bits.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Although 8-bits was the minimum in applications, programmers could choose up to a maximum of 24 bits for lighting precision.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] However, all calculations were still integer-based.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] One of the first graphics cards to support DirectX 9.0 natively was ATI's Radeon 9700, though the effect wasn't programmed into games for years afterwards.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] On August 23, 2003, Microsoft updated DirectX to DirectX 9.0b, which enabled the Pixel Shader 2.x (Extended) profile for ATI's Radeon X series and NVIDIA's GeForce FX series of graphics processing units.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] On August 9, 2004, Microsoft updated DirectX once more to DirectX 9.0c.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] This also exposed the Shader Model 3.0 profile for High-Level Shader Language (HLSL).
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Shader Model 3.0's lighting precision has a minimum of 32 bits as opposed to 2.0's 8-bit minimum.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Also all lighting-precision calculations are now floating-point based.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] NVIDIA states that contrast ratios using Shader Model 3.0 can be as high as 65535:1 using 32-bit lighting precision.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] At first, HDRR was only possible on video cards capable of Shader-Model-3.0 effects, but software developers soon added compatibility for Shader Model 2.0.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] As a side note, when referred to as Shader Model 3.0 HDR, HDRR is really done by FP16 blending.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] FP16 blending is not part of Shader Model 3.0, but is supported mostly by cards also capable of Shader Model 3.0 (exceptions include the GeForce 6200 series).
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] FP16 blending can be used as a faster way to render HDR in video games.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Shader Model 4.0 is a feature of DirectX 10, which was released with Windows Vista.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Shader Model 4.0 allows 128-bit HDR rendering, as opposed to 64-bit HDR in Shader Model 3.0 (although this is theoretically possible under Shader Model 3.0).
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] Shader Model 5.0 is a feature of DirectX 11.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] It allows 6:1 compression of HDR textures without noticeable loss, which is prevalent in previous versions of DirectX HDR texture compression techniques.
[src:bloom-effect/high-dynamic-range-rendering] It is possible to develop HDRR through GLSL shader starting from OpenGL 1.4 onwards.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] In radiometry, **radiance** is the radiant flux emitted, reflected, transmitted or received by a given surface, per unit solid angle per unit projected area.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] Radiance is used to characterize diffuse emission and reflection of electromagnetic radiation, and to quantify emission of neutrinos and other particles.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] The SI unit of radiance is the watt per steradian per square metre (W·sr−1·m−2).
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] It is a *directional* quantity: the radiance of a surface depends on the direction from which it is being observed.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] The related quantity spectral radiance is the radiance of a surface per unit frequency or wavelength, depending on whether the spectrum is taken as a function of frequency or of wavelength.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] Historically, radiance was called "intensity" and spectral radiance was called "specific intensity".
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] Many fields still use this nomenclature.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] It is especially dominant in heat transfer, astrophysics and astronomy.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] "Intensity" has many other meanings in physics, with the most common being power per unit area (so the radiance is the intensity per solid angle in this case).
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] Radiance is useful because it indicates how much of the power emitted, reflected, transmitted, or received by a surface will be received by an optical system looking at that surface from a specified angle of view.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] In this case, the solid angle of interest is the solid angle subtended by the optical system's entrance pupil.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] Since the eye is an optical system, radiance and its cousin luminance are good indicators of how bright an object will appear.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] For this reason, radiance and luminance are both sometimes called "brightness".
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] This usage is now discouraged (see the article Brightness for a discussion).
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] The nonstandard usage of "brightness" for "radiance" persists in some fields, notably laser physics.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] The radiance divided by the index of refraction squared is invariant in geometric optics.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] This means that for an ideal optical system in air, the radiance at the output is the same as the input radiance.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] This is sometimes called *conservation of radiance*.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] For real, passive, optical systems, the output radiance is *at most* equal to the input, unless the index of refraction changes.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] As an example, if you form a demagnified image with a lens, the optical power is concentrated into a smaller area, so the irradiance is higher at the image.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] The light at the image plane, however, fills a larger solid angle so the radiance comes out to be the same assuming there is no loss at the lens.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] Spectral radiance expresses radiance as a function of frequency or wavelength.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] Radiance is the integral of the spectral radiance over all frequencies or wavelengths.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] For radiation emitted by the surface of an ideal black body at a given temperature, spectral radiance is governed by Planck's law, while the integral of its radiance, over the hemisphere into which its surface radiates, is given by the Stefan–Boltzmann law.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] Its surface is Lambertian, so that its radiance is uniform with respect to angle of view, and is simply the Stefan–Boltzmann integral divided by π.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] This factor is obtained from the solid angle 2π steradians of a hemisphere decreased by integration over the cosine of the zenith angle.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] In general *L*e,Ω is a function of viewing direction, depending on *θ* through cos *θ* and azimuth angle through ∂Φe/∂Ω.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] For the special case of a Lambertian surface, ∂2Φe/(∂Ω ∂*A*) is proportional to cos *θ*, and *L*e,Ω is isotropic (independent of viewing direction).
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] When calculating the radiance emitted by a source, *A* refers to an area on the surface of the source, and Ω to the solid angle into which the light is emitted.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] When calculating radiance received by a detector, *A* refers to an area on the surface of the detector and Ω to the solid angle subtended by the source as viewed from that detector.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] When radiance is conserved, as discussed above, the radiance emitted by a source is the same as that received by a detector observing it.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] As the light travels through an ideal optical system, both the étendue and the radiant flux are conserved.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] In real systems, the étendue may increase (for example due to scattering) or the radiant flux may decrease (for example due to absorption) and, therefore, basic radiance may decrease.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] However, étendue may not decrease and radiant flux may not increase and, therefore, basic radiance may not increase.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] Alternative symbols sometimes seen: W or E for radiant energy, P or F for radiant flux, I for irradiance, W for radiant exitance.
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] Spectral quantities given per unit wavelength are denoted with suffix "*λ*".
[src:bloom-effect/radiance] Directional quantities are denoted with suffix "Ω".
